s%20class%20has%20its%20own%20transmission%20queue%20(AC).%20This%20means%20that%20based%20on%20the%20priority%20of%20the%20data%2C%20it%20will%20be%20placed%20in%20the%20corresponding%20queue%20waiting%20for%20transmission.%0A%20%20%20%20-%20**Per-queue%20EDCA%20functions%20with%20internal%20collision%20resolution**%3A%20Each%20queue%20has%20its%20own%20EDCA%20functions%2C%20which%20include%20algorithms%20for%20deciding%20when%20packets%20can%20start%20being%20transmitted.%20These%20features%20also%20include%20internal%20collision%20resolution%20mechanisms%20to%20handle%20collisions%20that%20occur%20when%20multiple%20packets%20attempt%20to%20use%20the%20same%20wireless%20channel%20at%20the%20same%20time.%0A%0A%23%23%20IFS%20in%20802.11%20DCF%3AContention%20between%20STAs%0A!%5Bimage%5D(https%3A%2F%2Fhackmd.io%2F_uploads%2FBkcg_7UhT.png)%0AThis%20figure%20shows%20the%20concept%20of%20Interframe%20Space%20(IFS)%20under%20the%20Distributed%20Coordination%20Function%20(DCF)%20in%20the%20IEEE%20802.11%20protocol.%20In%20the%20802.11%20Wireless%20LAN%20(WLAN)%20standard%2C%20DCF%20is%20a%20part%20of%20the%20Media%20Access%20Control%20(MAC)%20protocol%20used%20to%20control%20access%20contention%20between%20stations%20(STAs).%20Elements%20here%20include%3A%0A%0A-%20**DIFS%20(DCF%20Interframe%20Space)**%3A%20This%20is%20the%20lowest%20IFS%20and%20is%20used%20for%20instant%20access%20to%20data%20transfer%20when%20the%20media%20is%20idle%20for%20a%20duration%20equal%20to%20or%20exceeding%20DIFS.%0A-%20**PIFS%20(PCF%20Interframe%20Space)**%3A%20Used%20for%20access%20under%20the%20Point%20Coordination%20Function%20(PCF).%20It%20is%20shorter%20than%20DIFS%20and%20allows%20the%20point%20coordinator%20(PC)%20to%20access%20the%20medium%20faster%20in%20a%20distributed%20system.%0A-%20**SIFS%20(Short%20Interframe%20Space)**%3A%20It%20is%20the%20shortest%20of%20all%20IFS%20and%20is%20used%20for%20fast%20transmission%20of%20acknowledgment%20(ACK)%20packets%2C%20clear%20send%20(CTS)%20packets%20and%20fragmented%20packets.%0A-%20**Busy%20Medium**%3A%20Indicates%20that%20the%20medium%20is%20in%20use.%20(Channel%20status%20indication.%20If%20a%20station%20detects%20that%20the%20channel%20is%20busy%2C%20it%20means%20that%20there%20are%20other%20transmissions%20in%20progress%20at%20the%20current%20moment%20and%20must%20wait%20until%20the%20channel%20becomes%20free.)%0A-%20**Defer%20Access**%3A%20If%20the%20medium%20is%20busy%2C%20access%20must%20be%20deferred.%0A-%20**Contention%20Window**%3A%20A%20random%20delay%20that%20a%20site%20must%20wait%20before%20trying%20to%20access%20the%20medium.%20It%20randomizes%20access%20attempts%20to%20reduce%20the%20likelihood%20of%20collisions.%0A-%20**Backoff%20Window**%3A%20is%20part%20of%20the%20Contention%20Window%20and%20is%20part%20of%20the%20backoff%20algorithm%2C%20in%20which%20each%20STA%20randomly%20selects%20a%20time%20slot%20before%20attempting%20to%20transmit%20and%20decrements%20the%20backoff%20counter%20after%20each%20idle%20time%20slot.%0A-%20**Slot%20time**%3A%20is%20the%20smallest%20unit%20of%20time%2C%20used%20to%20define%20the%20time%20slot%20in%20the%20backoff%20window.%0A-%20**Select%20Slot%20and%20Decrement%20Backoff%20as%20long%20as%20medium%20is%20idle**%3A%20When%20the%20medium%20is%20idle%2C%20the%20STA%20will%20select%20a%20slot%20and%20start%20counting%20down%20its%20backoff%20counter.%20If%20the%20medium%20remains%20idle%20until%20the%20backoff%20counter%20reaches%20zero%2C%20the%20STA%20can%20attempt%20to%20transmit.%0A%0AThis%20process%20is%20to%20reduce%20collisions%20in%20the%20air%0A%23%23%20DCF%20Example%0A!%5BUntitled%20(15)%5D(https%3A%2F%2Fhackmd.io%2F_uploads%2FBJgq_mUha.png)%0A(DCF%20also%20exists%20in%20802.11e%2C%20but%20mainly%20as%20a%20fallback%20without%20QoS%20requirements.)%0A%23%23%20IFS%20in%20EDCF%3AContention%20between%20ACs%0A!%5BUntitled%20(16)%5D(https%3A%2F%2Fhackmd.io%2F_uploads%2FBJJiu7Ln6.png)%0AThe%20concept%20of%20TXOP%20in%20mac%20layer%0A%0AThe%20TXOP%20value%20may%20be%20specified%20in%20the%20configuration%20settings%20of%20the%20wireless%20access%20point%20(AP)%20or%20assigned%20by%20the%20network%20management%20system%20based%20on%20global%20policy.%0A%0A1.%20**SIFS%20(Short%20Interframe%20Space)**%3A%20The%20data%20frame%20is%20followed%20by%20a%20very%20short%20interval%2C%20used%20for%20operations%20with%20the%20highest%20priority%2C%20such%20as%20the%20receiver%20sending%20an%20acknowledgment%20frame%20(Ack).%0A2.%20**Acknowledgement%20Frame%20(Ack)**%3A%20The%20receiver%20sends%20an%20acknowledgment%20after%20SIFS%20to%20confirm%20that%20it%20has%20successfully%20received%20the%20previous%20data%20frame.%0A3.%20**DIFS%20(DCF%20Interframe%20Space)**%3A%20The%20standard%20time%20interval%20used%20in%20the%20Distributed%20Coordination%20Function%20(DCF)%20to%20start%20a%20new%20transmission%20attempt.%0A4.%20**PIFS%20(PCF%20Interframe%20Space)**%3A%20The%20time%20interval%20in%20Point%20Coordination%20Function%20(PCF)%20mode%2C%20which%20is%20shorter%20than%20DIFS%2C%20allows%20the%20central%20controller%20to%20prioritize%20access%20to%20the%20media.%0A5.%20**AIFS%5BAC_XX%5D%20and%20AIFS%5BAC_YY%5D**%3A%20These%20are%20the%20Arbitration%20Interframe%20Space%20in%20Enhanced%20Distributed%20Channel%20Access%20(EDCA)%2C%20used%20for%20traffic%20of%20different%20access%20categories%20(AC).%20Each%20type%20of%20traffic%20(such%20as%20background%2C%20best%20effort%2C%20video%20and%20voice)%20has%20its%20own%20AIFS%20to%20ensure%20QoS%20requirements%20are%20met.%20AIFS%5BAC_XX%5D%20and%20AIFS%5BAC_YY%5D%20represent%20different%20AIFS%20time%20intervals%20for%20traffic%20of%20different%20priorities.%0A6.%20**Contention%20Window**%3A%20This%20is%20a%20random%20wait%20time%20that%20determines%20how%20long%20a%20site%20should%20wait%20before%20attempting%20a%20transfer.%20It%20is%20designed%20to%20reduce%20the%20probability%20of%20collision.%20The%20size%20of%20the%20Contention%20Window%20is%20set%20based%20on%20each%20AC%2C%20not%20based%20on%20user%20priority.%0A7.%20**Next%20TXOP%20(Transmission%20Opportunity)**%3A%20This%20is%20the%20next%20transmission%20opportunity%2C%20that%20is%2C%20the%20time%20period%20during%20which%20the%20station%20can%20send%20a%20series%20of%20data%20frames%20without%20re-competing%20for%20the%20media.%0A%0A%23%23%20Arbitration%20Interframe%20Space(AIFS)%0A%0A-%20QSTA%20use%20AIFS%20to%20defer%20the%20contention%20window%20or%20transmission%20for%20each%20AC%0A-%20AIF%5BAC%5D%20%3D%20AIFSN%5BAC%5D%20x%20aSlotTime%20slot%20time%20%2B%20aSIFTime%0A%20%20%20%20%20-%20AIFSN%20(Arbitration%20Interframe%20Space%20Number)%20for%20each%20AC%20is%20broadcast%20via%20beacon%20frame%20containing%20%E2%80%98EDCA%20Parameter%20Set%E2%80%99%20element%0A-%20(DIFS%20%3D%202%20x%20aSlotTime%20%2B%20aSIFTime)%0A%20%20%20%20%20-%20**AIFS%5BAC%5D**%3A%20For%20a%20specific%20access%20class%20(AC)%2C%20this%20is%20the%20total%20time%20to%20wait%20after%20the%20channel%20becomes%20idle%20before%20data%20can%20be%20transmitted.%20AIFS%20can%20be%20different%20for%20each%20AC%2C%20allowing%20high-priority%20traffic%20to%20access%20the%20media%20faster.%0A%20%20%20%20%20-%20**AIFSN%5BAC%5D**%3A%20This%20is%20the%20AC-specific%20Arbitration%20Interframe%20Space%20Number%2C%20which%20determines%20the%20length%20of%20the%20AIFS.%20For%20high-priority%20traffic%2C%20the%20value%20of%20AIFSN%20is%20smaller%3B%20for%20low-priority%20traffic%2C%20the%20value%20of%20AIFSN%20is%20larger.%0A%20%20%20%20%20-%20**aSlotTime**%3A%20This%20is%20the%20length%20of%20the%20time%20slot%20in%20the%20802.11%20network.%20It%20is%20the%20basic%20unit%20of%20time%20and%20is%20used%20to%20calculate%20backoff%20time%20and%20AIFS.%20The%20time%20slot%20is%20fixed%20and%20determined%20by%20the%20physical%20conditions%20of%20the%20network.%0A%20%20%20%20%20-%20**aSIFSTime**%3A%20This%20is%20the%20shortest%20Interframe%20Space%2C%20used%20to%20separate%20the%20transmission%20of%20management%20and%20control%20frames%2C%20such%20as%20acknowledgment%20frames%20(ACK)%20and%20clear-to-send%20frames%20(CTS).%20It%20allows%20for%20quick%20responses%2C%20thus%20maintaining%20the%20efficiency%20of%20communication.%0A%0A%23%23%20EDCA%20Parameter%20Set%20Element%0A!%5BUntitled%20(3)%5D(https%3A%2F%2Fhackmd.io%2F_uploads%2FByQmZdKhp.png)%0AThis%20figure%20is%20a%20representation%20of%20the%20EDCA%20parameter%20settings%20for%20the%20QoS%20function%20in%20an%20802.11%20wireless%20network.%20In%20the%20802.11e%20standard%2C%20EDCA%20provides%20different%20priorities%20for%20different%20data%20flows%2C%20which%20are%20represented%20by%20different%20access%20categories%20(AC).%20This%20figure%20shows%20the%20structure%20of%20a%20QoS%20parameter%20element%20that%20defines%20the%20behavior%20of%20each%20AC.%20Key%20parts%20of%20the%20diagram%20include%3A%0A%0A1.%20**Element%20ID%20and%20Length**%3A%20Identifies%20the%20type%20and%20length%20of%20the%20information%20element.%0A2.%20**QoS%20Info**%3A%20Provides%20QoS-related%20information.%0A3.%20**AC%20parameter%20record**%3A%20For%20each%20AC%20category%20(AC_BE%2C%20AC_BK%2C%20AC_VI%2C%20AC_VO)%2C%20there%20is%20a%20parameter%20record%2C%20including%3A%0A%20%20%20%20%20-%20AIFSN%3A%20Arbitration%20Interframe%20Space%20Number%2C%20used%20to%20calculate%20AIFS.%0A%20%20%20%20%20-%20ACM%3A%20Admission%20Control%20Mandatory%2C%20indicating%20whether%20access%20control%20is%20necessary.%0A%20%20%20%20%20-%20ACI%3A%20Access%20Category%20Index%2C%20indicating%20the%20number%20of%20the%20AC.%0A%20%20%20%20%20-%20ECWmin%2FECWmax%3A%20Specify%20the%20minimum%2Fmaximum%20index%20for%20calculating%20Contention%20Window.%0A%20%20%20%20%20-%20TXOP%20Limit%3A%20The%20maximum%20transmission%20time%20allowed%20by%20this%20AC.%0A4.%20**CWmin%20and%20CWmax**%3A%20These%20are%20the%20actual%20minimum%20and%20maximum%20values%20of%20Contention%20Window%20calculated%20based%20on%20ECWmin%2FECWmax.%20CWmin%20and%20CWmax%20are%20important%20parameters%20u