<body style="display:none;">
    <div id="toasts-container" class="toasts-container z-[2000]"></div>
    <div id="publish-page"># 802.11e
![螢幕擷取畫面 2024-02-23 085742 (1)](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/SydcdzUh6.png)
- **IEEE 802.1 Management**: This refers to network management and includes bridging and Virtual LANs (VLANs). The standards like 802.1d for bridging and 802.1q for VLAN are specified here.
- **802.2 Logical link control (LLC)**: This part of the IEEE 802 standard defines the Logical Link Control, which is the top sublayer in the data link layer. LLC is used for addressing and control of the data link.
- **802.3**: This refers to Ethernet, a wired networking standard. It includes both the Media Access Control (MAC) sublayer and the Physical Layer (PHY).
- **802.5**: This is for Token Ring networks, also detailing the MAC and PHY layers
- **802.11**: This is the standard for wireless networking, commonly known as Wi-Fi. It also has MAC and PHY sublayers, with various PHY types like FHSS, DSSS, OFDM, and HR/DSSS, which refer to different types of radio technologies used.
- **802.11 Variants**:
    - **802.11 FHSS PHY**: Frequency-Hopping Spread Spectrum Physical Layer.
    - **802.11 DSSS PHY**: Direct-Sequence Spread Spectrum Physical Layer.
    - **802.11a OFDM PHY**: Orthogonal Frequency-Division Multiplexing for 802.11a, a standard for wireless networking that operates in the 5 GHz band.
    - **802.11b/g HR/DSSS PHY**: High Rate/Direct Sequence Spread Spectrum for 802.11b/g, standards for wireless networking that operate in the 2.4 GHz band.
## QoS Requirement

- Parameters of traffic stream
    - Controlled transmission rate
        - Peak rate &amp; Average rate
    - Controlled Service Interval
        - Minimum &amp; Maximum
    - Burst Size on peak rate
- Requirements
    - Bounded Delay (for real-time &amp; smooth interaction)
    - Bounded Jitter (for smooth playout)
- Solution in device: Jitter Buffer
- Solution in network: Prioritized Transmission

## Two Kinds of QoS

1. Parameterized QoS:
    1. A strict QoS requirement expressed quantitatively in
    terms of data rate, delay bound etc. (ex. BW of 10 Mbps,
    delay bound of 10ms)
2. Prioritized QoS:
    1. Loose QoS requirement expressed in terms of relative
    delivery priorit

## Is 802.11 enough for QoS?

1. DCF can not provide QoS trivially
    1. DCF: &#34;Distributed Coordination Function&#34;, which is a basic media access control (MAC) protocol in the IEEE 802.11 wireless LAN standard. uses a CSMA/CA mechanism.
2. PCF is not enough（Point Coordination Function）
    1. PCF : An optional addition to DCF, designed to support networks containing latency-sensitive data transmission
    2. Only 1 frame can be sent at each polling
    3. Point Coordinator (PC) does not know the
    QoS requirement of traffic
    4. Can not guarantee the delay and jitter
    bound

## Brief of IEEE 802.11e

- Defined at IEEE 802.11 Task Group E
- Goal: Providing QoS
    - Minimize Latency
    - Maximize throughput
    - Define traffic models for both Ad-hoc and
    Infrastructure
- Approach: Enhance the MAC (802.11)

## Major Enhancements in 802.11e

- Basic elements for QoS
    - Traffic Differentiation
    - Concept of Transmission Opportunity (TXOP)
- New Contention-based channel access
    - Enhanced Distributed Channel Access (EDCA) (Contention-based)

- New Contention-free channel acces
    - HCF Controlled Channel Access (HCCA) (Contention Free)

- Other new mechanisms for higher throughput
    - Block Acknowledgement (Block Ack)
    - Direct Link Setup (DLS)
    - Automatic Power-Save Delivery (APSD)
        

## Terms

- QoS Facility
    - The mechanisms for QoS defined in 802.11e
- QAP
    - Access Point supporting QoS facility
- QSTA
    - Station supporting QoS facility
- QBSS
- Hybrid Coorinator (HC)
- Access Category (AC)
- User Priority (UP)
- Traffic Category (TC)
- Traffic Specification (TSPEC)
- Traffic Stream (TS)
- Traffic Identifier (TID)

# Traffic Differentiation

## Classification of QoS Data

- New frame subtype: QoS Data
![Untitled](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/ByZQYf8n6.png)
- Each MSDU of QoS Data is classified as one kind of traffic
    - Identified by TID field in frame header
        - EX:
            Voice traffic: TID = 1
            Video traffic: TID = 2
            Data traffic: TID = 3
            
- Two types of traffic classification(Ensure critical data such as voice and video gets the network resources it needs.)
    - By User Priority (UP)(for prioritized QoS)
    - By Traffic Specification (TSPEC)(for parameterized QoS

## User Priority

- 8 User Priorities:
    - Identical to IEEE 802.1D priority tags
![Untitled (1)](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/rkRUYfL3T.png)
- Priority Determination of MSDU
    - Directly:
        - provided at MAC SAP by upper-layer software
    - Indirectly:
        - defined in TSPEC’s


## Access Category (AC)

- Rules
    - One UP(User Priority) belongs to one AC
    - Each AC contains two UP
    - Traffic of higher UP will be transmitted first in one AC
- In EDCA, media access is based on the AC of MSDU
- 4 AC’s are defined
    - AC_BK (background)
    - AC_BE (best-effort)
    - AC_VI (Video)
    - AC_VO (Voice)
- In EDCA, the size of Contention-Window (CW) Inter-frame space (IFS) is dependent on AC

## Traffic Specification
- Traffic Specification (TSPEC)
    - Characteristics of traffic streams created by negotiation between QSTA（Quality of Service Traffic Stream Aware） and HC ( Hybrid Coordinator）
    - HC can schedule the polling輪巡 within CFP（Contention-Free Period） and the
    data transmission of the TS accordingly
    - At most 8 TSPEC can be registered
    - Identified by TSID（Traffic Stream Identifier ) (0~7)
- TSPEC Setup &amp; Delete
    - Use Management Frame with new subtype Action
        - ADDTS request &amp; ADDTS response: for TSPEC setup
        - DELTS: for TSPEC delete

![Untitled (2)](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/B1aiYfIn6.png)

## MAC Frame Formats

- MAC frame format (QoS Data):
![Untitled (3)](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/Hk6htfU2a.png)
* QoS Control Field:

![Untitled (4)](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/SJx0KMU26.png)
- In QoS control field
    - TID: Traffic Identifier
    - EOSP: End of Service Period
        - Service period is ended after successful
        transmission of this frame
        - Used with APSD(Automatic Power-Save Delivery)
    - QAP PS Buffer State
![Untitled (5)](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/H1y15fL2a.png)
- Distinguish MSDUs of different traffic types
    - Range: 0-15
![Untitled (6)](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/HygxqzUnT.png)

## Action Frames: ADDTS request &amp; ADDTS response
![Untitled (7)](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/HJVzcfLna.png)
