## Traffic Classification (TCLAS)Element
- For identifying the TS to which the incoming MSDUs belong
![Untitled (10)](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/rkAN5zL3a.png)
![Untitled (11)](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/H1NBcM82T.png)
## Schedule Element
- HC contains Schedule element in ADDTS response if incoming ADDTS request’s TS_INFO.Schedule = 1.
- If TS_Info.Access_Policy includes EDCA, the schedule element indicate the polling schedule for this TS in HCF
- TS_Info.APSD = 1, the schedule element indicate the wakeup schedule for transmission

![Untitled (12)](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/ryOUcG8n6.png)
# Hybrid Coordination Function(HCF)
## HCF Brief

- In 802.11, two access methods
    - Distributed Coordination Function (DCF)
    - Point Coordination Function (PCF)
- In 802.11e, HCF access method is added,
including
    - Contention-Based channel access– EDCA
        - Combined with DCF
    - Controlled channel access – HCCA
        - Similar to PCF but with enhancement

## MAC Architecture
![Untitled (14)](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/Skp7S7Uha.png)
* This diagram shows how to choose different access methods based on different requirements and QoS parameters. As can be seen from the arrow on the left, for QoS services that require priority processing, PCF or HCF must be used. For services that do not require competition, that is, non-QoS services, you can choose not to use PCF, which is usually optional. The arrow on the right indicates that HCF is necessary for QoS services that require parameterization, especially the HCCA part.

## EDCA

- Difference from original DCF
    - Contention between ACs (Not STAs)
    - AC Contends for Transmission Opportunity(TXOP) in unit of 32 microseconds.
    - New Inter-frame Space (IFS) for each AC:Arbitration Interframe Space (AIFS)
## Reference implementation
![Untitled](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/rkAdF6826.png)
* EDCA reference implementation model:

    - **MSDU, UP**: This represents the MAC Service Data Unit (MSDU) and User Priority (UP). MSDU is a data unit that is sent to the MAC sublayer to prepare for encapsulation, and the user priority is an attribute of the data packet that is used to determine the priority of its transmission.
    - **Mapping to Access Category**: This means that data will be mapped to different access categories (Access Category, AC) based on user priority. In EDCA, there are four different access categories, which are used for data transmission with different priorities.
    - **Transmit queues for ACs**: Each access class has its own transmission queue (AC). This means that based on the priority of the data, it will be placed in the corresponding queue waiting for transmission.
    - **Per-queue EDCA functions with internal collision resolution**: Each queue has its own EDCA functions, which include algorithms for deciding when packets can start being transmitted. These features also include internal collision resolution mechanisms to handle collisions that occur when multiple packets attempt to use the same wireless channel at the same time.

## IFS in 802.11 DCF:Contention between STAs
![image](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/Bkcg_7UhT.png)
This figure shows the concept of Interframe Space (IFS) under the Distributed Coordination Function (DCF) in the IEEE 802.11 protocol. In the 802.11 Wireless LAN (WLAN) standard, DCF is a part of the Media Access Control (MAC) protocol used to control access contention between stations (STAs). Elements here include:

- **DIFS (DCF Interframe Space)**: This is the lowest IFS and is used for instant access to data transfer when the media is idle for a duration equal to or exceeding DIFS.
- **PIFS (PCF Interframe Space)**: Used for access under the Point Coordination Function (PCF). It is shorter than DIFS and allows the point coordinator (PC) to access the medium faster in a distributed system.
- **SIFS (Short Interframe Space)**: It is the shortest of all IFS and is used for fast transmission of acknowledgment (ACK) packets, clear send (CTS) packets and fragmented packets.
- **Busy Medium**: Indicates that the medium is in use. (Channel status indication. If a station detects that the channel is busy, it means that there are other transmissions in progress at the current moment and must wait until the channel becomes free.)
- **Defer Access**: If the medium is busy, access must be deferred.
- **Contention Window**: A random delay that a site must wait before trying to access the medium. It randomizes access attempts to reduce the likelihood of collisions.
- **Backoff Window**: is part of the Contention Window and is part of the backoff algorithm, in which each STA randomly selects a time slot before attempting to transmit and decrements the backoff counter after each idle time slot.
- **Slot time**: is the smallest unit of time, used to define the time slot in the backoff window.
- **Select Slot and Decrement Backoff as long as medium is idle**: When the medium is idle, the STA will select a slot and start counting down its backoff counter. If the medium remains idle until the backoff counter reaches zero, the STA can attempt to transmit.

This process is to reduce collisions in the air
## DCF Example
![Untitled (15)](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/BJgq_mUha.png)
(DCF also exists in 802.11e, but mainly as a fallback without QoS requirements.)
## IFS in EDCF:Contention between ACs
![Untitled (16)](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/BJJiu7Ln6.png)
The concept of TXOP in mac layer

The TXOP value may be specified in the configuration settings of the wireless access point (AP) or assigned by the network management system based on global policy.

1. **SIFS (Short Interframe Space)**: The data frame is followed by a very short interval, used for operations with the highest priority, such as the receiver sending an acknowledgment frame (Ack).
2. **Acknowledgement Frame (Ack)**: The receiver sends an acknowledgment after SIFS to confirm that it has successfully received the previous data frame.
3. **DIFS (DCF Interframe Space)**: The standard time interval used in the Distributed Coordination Function (DCF) to start a new transmission attempt.
4. **PIFS (PCF Interframe Space)**: The time interval in Point Coordination Function (PCF) mode, which is shorter than DIFS, allows the central controller to prioritize access to the media.
5. **AIFS[AC_XX] and AIFS[AC_YY]**: These are the Arbitration Interframe Space in Enhanced Distributed Channel Access (EDCA), used for traffic of different access categories (AC). Each type of traffic (such as background, best effort, video and voice) has its own AIFS to ensure QoS requirements are met. AIFS[AC_XX] and AIFS[AC_YY] represent different AIFS time intervals for traffic of different priorities.
6. **Contention Window**: This is a random wait time that determines how long a site should wait before attempting a transfer. It is designed to reduce the probability of collision. The size of the Contention Window is set based on each AC, not based on user priority.
7. **Next TXOP (Transmission Opportunity)**: This is the next transmission opportunity, that is, the time period during which the station can send a series of data frames without re-competing for the media.

## Arbitration Interframe Space(AIFS)

- QSTA use AIFS to defer the contention window or transmission for each AC
- AIF[AC] = AIFSN[AC] x aSlotTime slot time + aSIFTime
     - AIFSN (Arbitration Interframe Space Number) for each AC is broadcast via beacon frame containing ‘EDCA Parameter Set’ element
- (DIFS = 2 x aSlotTime + aSIFTime)
     - **AIFS[AC]**: For a specific access class (AC), this is the total time to wait after the channel becomes idle before data can be transmitted. AIFS can be different for each AC, allowing high-priority traffic to access the media faster.
     - **AIFSN[AC]**: This is the AC-specific Arbitration Interframe Space Number, which determines the length of the AIFS. For high-priority traffic, the value of AIFSN is smaller; for low-priority traffic, the value of AIFSN is larger.
     - **aSlotTime**: This is the length of the time slot in the 802.11 network. It is the basic unit of time and is used to calculate backoff time and AIFS. The time slot is fixed and determined by the physical conditions of the network.
     - **aSIFSTime**: This is the shortest Interframe Space, used to separate the transmission of management and control frames, such as acknowledgment frames (ACK) and clear-to-send frames (CTS). It allows for quick responses, thus maintaining the efficiency of communication.

## EDCA Parameter Set Element
![Untitled (3)](https://hackmd.io/_uploads/ByQmZdKhp.png)
This figure is a representation of the EDCA parameter settings for the QoS function in an 802.11 wireless network. In the 802.11e standard, EDCA provides different priorities for different data flows, which are represented by different access categories (AC). This figure shows the structure of a QoS parameter element that defines the behavior of each AC. Key parts of the diagram include:

1. **Element ID and Length**: Identifies the type and length of the information element.
2. **QoS Info**: Provides QoS-related information.
3. **AC parameter record**: For each AC category (AC_BE, AC_BK, AC_VI, AC_VO), there is a parameter record, including:
     - AIFSN: Arbitration Interframe Space Number, used to calculate AIFS.
     - ACM: Admission Control Mandatory, indicating whether access control is necessary.
     - ACI: Access Category Index, indicating the number of the AC.
     - ECWmin/ECWmax: Specify the minimum/maximum index for calculating Contention Window.
     - TXOP Limit: The maximum transmission time allowed by this AC.
4. **CWmin and CWmax**: These are the actual minimum and maximum values of Contention Window calculated based on ECWmin/ECWmax. CWmin and CWmax are important parameters used in the backoff algorithm to determine the number of random time slots that a STA must wait for before attempting to transmit.
5. **Bits and Bytes**: The representation of Bits and Octets helps understand the size of each field in the parameter record.</div>
